'''Carboxytherapy''' is a non-surgical cosmetic medicine treatment. Carboxytherapy employs injections to infuse gaseous [[carbon dioxide]] below the [[skin]] into the subcutaneous tissue through a needle. It claims to kill [[fat]] cells, stimulate [[blood]] flow, improve the skin's elasticity and reduce the appearance of [[cellulite]]<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=17168416 |year=2006 |last1=Koutná |first1=N |title=Karboxyterapie – nová neinvazivní metoda estetické medicíny |trans-title=Carboxytherapy – A New Non-invasive Method in Aesthetic Medicine |language=Czech |volume=145 |issue=11 |pages=841–3 |journal=Časopis Lékařů Českých |url=http://www.prolekare.cz/casopis-lekaru-ceskych-clanek?id=3162}}</ref> although it has not been clinically tested nor approved by the FDA.<ref>{{cite press release | year=2009 | title=Carboxytherapy And Mesotherapy Unproven |url=http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/releases/159481.php}}</ref> It has also become a popular treatment for [[stretch marks]].<ref name="PrendergastShiffman2011">{{cite book|last1=Prendergast|first1=Peter M.|last2=Shiffman|first2=Melvin A.|title=Aesthetic Medicine: Art and Techniques|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_yL0jc8DVsIC&pg=PA554|date= 2011|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-20113-4|page=554}}</ref>

