{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}} {{About|the venue in Florida|the former Broadway theatre|New Century Theatre}} {{Infobox venue | name = Venice Theatre | nickname = | former names = Venice Little Theatre | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | address = 140 West Tampa Avenue | location = [[Venice, Florida|Venice]], [[Florida]] | coordinates = {{Coord|27.10108|-82.4451|type:landmark_region:US-FL|display=inline,title}}<!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | type = Theatre | genre = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = {{start date|1950}}<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | renovated = | expanded = | owner = | operator = | surface = | production = | cost = | architect = | builder = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = {{Unbulleted list|432 (Mainstage)|90 (Pinkerton Theater)}} | record_attendance = | dimensions = | acreage = | volume = | embedded = | website = {{URL|www.venicestage.com}}<!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | publictransit = }} '''Venice Theatre''' is a [[community theater]] in [[Venice, Florida|Venice]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weber|first=Kristin|title=Venice Theatre announces 64th Season|url=http://venice.wtsp.com/news/arts-culture/163904-venice-theatre-announces-64th-season|publisher=venice.wtsp.com|accessdate=February 26, 2013}}</ref> Formerly Venice Little Theatre, the Venice Theatre is one of the largest community theaters in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Venice Theatre History {{!}} Venice Theatre|url = https://venicestage.com/about/history-of-venice-theatre/|website = Venice Theatre|access-date = February 4, 2016|language = en-US}}</ref>
==History== The theatre operates at one the former buildings of the [[Kentucky Military Institute]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://venicestage.com/about/history-of-venice-theatre/#tab-3-1 |title=Venice Threate History |website=Venice Theatre |access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> KMI closed its Venice campus in 1971 and Venice Theatre acquired the building on 140 West Tampa Avenue in 1973 for $78,000 ({{inflation|US-GDP|78000|1973|fmt=eq|r=-3}})<!--Using US-GDP as its a government transaction--> and converting the building to a theatre required an additional $225,000 ({{inflation|US-GDP|225000|1973|fmt=eq|r=-3}}).
